  "prompt": "What is acceleration of a body moving with uniform velocity?",
  "response": "When a body is moving with uniform velocity, its acceleration is zero. Let me explain this in detail:\n\n1. Uniform velocity means:\n- The speed of the body remains constant\n- The direction of motion does not change\n- There is no change in velocity over time\n\n2. Acceleration definition:\n- Acceleration is the rate of change of velocity with respect to time\n- It is calculated as: a = (v2 - v1) / t\n- Where a = acceleration, v1 = initial velocity, v2 = final velocity, t = time interval\n\n3. In uniform velocity:\n- Initial velocity (v1) = Final velocity (v2)\n- Change in velocity = 0\n- Therefore, acceleration = 0 m/s\u00b2\n\nExample:\n- A car moving at a constant speed of 60 km/hr on a straight road\n- No change in speed or direction\n- Acceleration = 0 m/s\u00b2\n\nKey points:\n- Zero acceleration doesn't mean the body is stationary\n- It means the body is moving at a constant velocity\n- No net force is acting on the body to change its motion",
